==English==

===Etymology===
{{compound|en|moon|struck}}. Compare {{cog|nds-de|maansüchtig}}, {{cog|de|mondsüchtig}}.

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# {{lb|en|obsolete}} [[crazy|Crazy]] or [[insane]] when affected by the [[phase]]s of the [[Moon]].
#* {{RQ:Milton PL|11|passage=And '''moon-struck''' madness, pining atrophy}}
# {{lb|en|by extension}} Showing [[irrational]] behaviour, especially of a [[romantic]] or [[sentimental]] nature.
#* '''1902''', {{w|William James}}, ''The Varieties of Religious Experience'', Lectures 4 & 5:
#*: [W]e can also overlook the verbiage of a good deal of the mind-cure literature, some of which is so '''moonstruck''' with optimism and so vaguely expressed that an academically trained intellect finds it almost impossible to read it at all.
#* '''1925''', {{w|Sinclair Lewis}}, ''Arrowsmith'', Chapter 21, IV:
#*: The full moon was spacious now behind the maples. The seedy Pickerbaugh domain was enchanted […] and over all the world was the proper witchery of '''moonstruck''' love.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} Made sick, or (like fishes) unsuitable for food, by the supposed [[influence]] of the Moon.

